entries.meaning: (obsolete) A person employed to spread or transport dung.
examples: But I will bring over you Dungers with great Dung-Forks, who shall dung thee from off the earth, with thy great heap, as an abominable sin-dunghill.
[Worms are] the natural diggers and dungers of land, worm-casts being nothing more than the dung of the worm.

entries.meaning: (obsolete) A person employed in the dunging of textiles.

description: From the "dung" sound often made by a worn-out engine.

entries.meaning: (Australia, New Zealand) An old, worn-out machine, especially a car.
examples: I got a free loaner. And this was quite a new car, too. Not like the clunky old dunger without a working heater I had to battle with on a previous occasion in the dead of winter.
